1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 {This is the soundest reply.} a6 5. dxc5 Qa5 
6. Nf3 Ne4 7. Qxd5 Nxc3 ({This is clearly stronger than} 7... Nxc5 {.}) 8. Qd2 
{[%cal Gd2a5][%csl Rc3,Ra5] Intending to recapture on c3 with the Queen.} Qxc5 
9. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 10. bxc3 {[%cal Ba1b1,Gb1b7][%csl Rc3,Rc2] White's extra pawn is 
less important here than his slight lead in development and open b- and d-files 
with which he can pressure Black's position.} Nd7 11. Rb1 {[%cal Gb1b7]} g6 
{This looks like a good way for Black to finish his development. However, the 
issue is that if he ever moves the d7-Knight to a different location, White can 
play Be5 forcing the exchange of dark-squared Bishops.} 12. c4 {[%cal 
Gg7a1][%csl Rc3] Black will play ...Bg7 soon, so it makes sense to vacate the 
a1-h8 diagonal.} Bg7 13. Be2 Bc3+ 14. Kd1 {[%cal Gd1c2,Gd1c1] The King can help 
in defending the Queenside.} O-O 15. Kc1 Nc5 16. Be5 {[%cal Be5c3]} Ne4 {[%cal 
Ge4c3,Ge4f2][%csl Rf2]} 17. Rf1 {[%cal Gf1f2]} Rd8 18. Bd3 {[%cal 
Gd3e4,Ge5c3][%csl Re4]} Bxe5 19. Nxe5 {[%csl Gc4,Gc2] White is a pawn up and 
although it is a doubled c-pawn, it is still a pawn. White will be playing for 2 
results.} *

