6. Nf3 Qxc5 7. Be2 Nc6 8. O-O Bf5 9. Na4 Qa7 10. Rc1 {This is also good.} e6 11. 
c4 {[%cal Gc1c8] When you're ahead in development it is a good idea to open up 
the position for your pieces.} dxc4 12. Rxc4 Rd8 13. Qc1 {[%cal 
Gc1c6,Bf3e5][%csl Gc4,Gc1] White increases his pressure on the c-file and then 
forces it open with Ne5.} Be7 14. Ne5 {[%cal Be5c6,Gc1c7]} Nxe5 15. Bxe5 O-O 16. 
Rd1 Nd5 17. Nc3 {[%cal Bc3d5,Bc4c7] White has a slight advantage due the better 
placement of his pieces. It must be acknowleged that this is not very 
significant, but White is to be preferred.} *

