1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 {This is the soundest reply.} a6 5. dxc5 Nc6 
6. a3 e5 7. Bg5 d4 {This advance does not have the desired effect.} 8. exd4 exd4 
9. Ne4 {[%cal Ge4f6,Gg5d8][%csl Rf6]} h6 ({Or} 9... Be7 10. Bxf6 {and Black has 
to take back with the g-pawn to prevent Nd6+.}) ({Note that} 9... Qa5+ $2 
{doesn't work after} 10. b4 $1 Nxb4 11. axb4 Qxb4+ 12. Bd2 {and White is simply 
a piece up.}) 10. Nxf6+ gxf6 11. Bf4 Bxc5 {[%csl Rf6,Rf7,Rh6,Rd4] Black has 
regained his pawn but his pawn structure is ruined.} 12. Nf3 {[%cal 
Bf1e2,Be1g1]} Ne5 13. Be2 {White has a much better structure and safer king. In 
terms of an opening advantage it ticks many boxes.} *

