1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 {This is the soundest reply.} a6 5. dxc5 e6 
6. Na4 {[%cal Ga4c5,Ga4b6][%csl Gc5,Rb6,Ra8] Threatening Nb6 and making Black 
work to regain the c5-pawn.} Qa5+ {[%csl Ra4,Re1]} 7. c3 {[%cal Gd1a4,Bb2b4] 
Threatening b2-b4 when Black isn't seeing his pawn back anytime soon, so he has 
to make haste.} Bxc5 8. Nxc5 Qxc5 9. Nf3 {[%cal Bf1d3][%csl Ge5,Gd4] White has 
the Bishop pair and control over the dark squares. He should finish development 
and then open up the position with c3-c4 or e3-e4.} Nc6 10. Bd3 ({Carlsen-So, 
Paris Blitz 2017 continued} 10. Bd3 10... h6 11. Ne5 O-O 12. O-O Qe7 13. c4 Nxe5 
14. Bxe5 dxc4 15. Bxc4 Rd8 16. Qf3 {, when White had the bishop pair in an open 
position which was the root of his advantage. Carlsen went on to win in 25 
moves.}) *

