1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 {This is the soundest reply.} cxd4 5. exd4 
a6 {Black has prevented us from getting any counterplay based on dxc5 or Nb5, 
but this has cost him precious time.} 6. Nf3 {[%cal Bf3e5][%csl Ge5] Played by 
Rapport.} g6 7. Ne5 {[%cal Bd1f3,Be1c1][%csl Ge5] The Knight is powerfully 
positioned here.} Nbd7 8. Qf3 {[%cal Be1c1,Gc3d5,Gf3d5][%csl Rd5]} Bg7 9. h4 
{[%cal Bh4h5,Gf3d5,Gc3d5,Be1c1][%csl Rd5] I simply cannot resist pushing Harry 
the h-pawn when I get a clear opportunity to do so. h5 is very much in play as 
Black's f6-Knight is covering the d5-pawn.} O-O 10. O-O-O Qa5 11. h5 {[%cal 
Gh1h7][%csl Rg6]} Nxh5 12. Rxh5 {A typical exchange sacrifice that gives White a 
strong attack.} gxh5 13. Qxh5 {[%cal Bf1d3,Bd1h1,Bf4h6][%csl Rh7,Rg7]} Nf6 
{[%cal Gf6h5][%csl Rh5] Even though Black can immediately bring the other Knight 
to the defense, his position is still very hard to defend.} 14. Qh4 {[%cal 
Bf1d3,Bd1h1] Keeping the Queen actively posted. White can continue with moves 
like Bd3 and Rh1 piling up on h7, or Bh6 trying to weaken the dark squares 
around Black's King further.} Be6 15. Bd3 Rfc8 {[%cal Gc8c3,Ga5c3][%csl Rc3] 
Despite being an exchange up Black's position is on the verge of collapse.} 16. 
Nb1 (16. Ne2 $6 {is less strong because after} 16... Qxa2 {Black will have the 
added option of ...Qa1+.}) ({After} 16. Bh6 Bxh6 17. Qxh6 Rxc3 $1 {Black has at 
least a draw.}) Kf8 ({In case of} 16... Qxa2 {White can play} 17. Bh6 Bxh6 18. 
Qxh6 $18 {followed by Rh1 or even g4-g5 with a decisive attack.}) 17. Bh6 Bxh6+ 
18. Qxh6+ Ke8 19. Qg7 {[%cal Bg7h8] Threatening Qh8+.} Kd8 20. Qf8+ {[%cal 
Ge5f7,Gf8e7,Gf8f7][%csl Rd8,Re7,Rf7]} Ne8 21. Nxf7+ Bxf7 22. Qxf7 {[%cal 
Gd3h7,Gf7h7][%csl Rh7,Rd8] Black's position is in total disarray and the h7-pawn 
is falling.} *

