1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 {This is the soundest reply.} cxd4 5. exd4 
a6 6. Nf3 {Played by Rapport.} Bf5 7. Ne5 {[%cal Bg2g4,Bh2h4][%csl Ge5] Now 
Black will experience problems with his light-squared Bishop if he plays ...e6.} 
e6 8. g4 {[%cal Ge5g4,Gd1g4][%csl Rf5]} Bg6 9. h4 {[%cal Bh4h5][%csl Rg6]} Ne4 
10. h5 {[%csl Rg6]} Nxc3 11. bxc3 {[%csl Rg6]} Be4 12. f3 {[%csl Re4] The Bishop 
is trapped, but Black can somewhat limit the damage.} f6 {[%csl Re5]} 13. Nc4 
{[%cal Bd5c4,Bf3e4][%csl Re4]} dxc4 14. fxe4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4,Gf1] White has 
central control, more space and the Bishop pair. He has a clear advantage.} *

