1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 {This is the soundest reply.} cxd4 5. exd4 
a6 6. Nf3 {Played by Rapport.} Nc6 7. Ne5 e6 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Na4 {This is 
intended to prevent Black playing ...c5 easily and targets the dark squares. It 
has been the choice of Rapport and Howell amongst others. It should be said that 
this is one of Black's soundest ways of meeting this opening but White's 
position is easier to play and the pawn structure and piece placements are 
marginally favourable.} Bd6 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. Bd3 e5 {[%cal Be5e4]} 12. dxe5 
{White should not allow ...e4.} Qxe5+ 13. Qe2 Qxe2+ 14. Kxe2 {[%cal 
Ga4c5,Bh1e1,Ba1d1][%csl Rc6,Rd5,Gc5] In honesty this position is objectively 
equal. However, if an opponent responds to an opening with a series of solid 
moves, although we wish for more we find ourselves in a position which is very 
comfortable and one which we should know better than our opponent.} *

