1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 {This is the soundest reply.} cxd4 5. exd4 
a6 6. Nf3 {Played by Rapport.} Bg4 7. h3 Bh5 8. g4 Bg6 9. Ne5 Nc6 10. h4 {This 
threatens h5, trapping Black's light-squared bishop.} Qb6 {[%cal 
Gb6b2,Gb6d4,Gc6d4][%csl Rb2,Rd4] This is the only decent reply to the threat of 
h5.} 11. Nxc6 (11. h5 {is also strong but leads to a lot of complications, 
whereas 11. Nxc6 removes Black's pressure while keeping the threat of h4-h5.}) 
bxc6 12. Na4 {[%cal Bh4h5,Ga4b6,Ga4b2][%csl Rb6,Gb2] Attacking the Queen and at 
the same time protecting b2 and threatening h5.} Qa5+ {After other moves White 
immediately wins a piece with 13. h5.} 13. c3 e6 ({Black can play} 13... h6 {, 
but after} 14. Qb3 $1 {White gains a decisive initiative on the Queenside - he 
is threatening Qb7. For example,} 14... Rd8 15. Nc5 $18 {and Black can't do 
anything against the threat of Nb7.}) 14. b4 {[%cal Bh4h5][%csl Ra5,Rg6] Black 
must now sacrifice his dark-squared Bishop, as otherwise his light-squared 
Bishop will be trapped by h5 and if ...Be4 then f3.} ({The immediate} 14. h5 {is 
less accurate, since after} 14... Be4 15. f3 Bxf3 $1 16. Qxf3 {Black regains the 
piece with} 16... Qxa4 {.}) Bxb4 15. cxb4 Qxb4+ 16. Ke2 {White has won a piece 
but been forced to move his king to e2. The material gain is worth it.} Nxg4 17. 
h5 {[%csl Rg6]} Bf5 18. a3 {[%csl Rb4] Black's Queen is forced back, 
neutralizing Black's initiative.} Qa5 19. Bh3 {[%cal Be2f1,Bf1g2,Bf4g3] White's 
extra piece gives a near winning advantage.} *

