1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4 Bf5 4. f3 c6 {This has been played but should not be 
critical. As ever though, it is always best to be prepared.} 5. g4 {[%csl Rf5] 
Gaining space and chasing Black's Bishop around.} Bg6 6. h4 {[%cal Bh4h5][%csl 
Rg6]} h6 ({This is an alternative to} 6... h5 {, but white already has a 
comfortable position. Play continues in line with the general themes of the 
opening.}) 7. e3 {[%cal Bf1d3,Bd3g6][%csl Rg6]} e6 8. Bd3 {[%cal Bd3g6,Bg1e2] 
Not committing to an advance of the h-pawn in order to retain the option of g5 
with maximum effect.} Bxd3 9. Qxd3 {[%cal Bg1e2,Be1f2,Bg4g5,Be1c1] White can 
continue to develop, connect the rooks and eventually play the move g4-g5.} Nbd7 
10. Nge2 Qa5 11. a3 {[%cal Ga3b4][%csl Gb4] Preventing ...Bb4 and also making it 
harder for Black to break with ...c5, since after dxc5 Bxc5 White could play b4 
with a fork.} Rc8 12. Kf2 {[%csl Ga1,Gh1] Castling queenside would be too risky 
in this situation. The king is perfectly safe on f2.} Qd8 13. Ng3 {[%cal 
Bg4g5,Ba1g1][%csl Rf6] There are chances for both sides here but White has a 
lead in development, more space and threats of further kingside expansion. Black 
is totally reliant on the ...c5 break. I would definitely prefer White's 
position.} *

