1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4 Bf5 4. f3 e6 {This locks the Bishop outside the pawn 
chain, inviting White to attack it.} 5. g4 {[%csl Rf5]} Bg6 6. h4 {[%cal 
Bh4h5][%csl Rg6]} h5 7. g5 {[%csl Rf6]} Nfd7 8. e3 {[%cal Bf1d3,Bd3g6] One idea 
after Black has played ...h6 or ...h5 to safeguard his g6-Bishop is to challenge 
it with Bd3, since an exchange of Bishops will highlight the weakened light 
squares on the Kingside.} c5 {This allows our typical Jobava London attack.} 9. 
Nb5 {[%cal Gb5c7][%csl Rc7]} Na6 10. c3 {[%cal Gc3b4][%csl Gb4,Ra6,Ra8]} Be7 11. 
Bg3 {[%cal Bg1h3,Bh3f4,Gf4g6,Gf4h5][%csl Rg6,Rh5] A clever move, intending 
Nh3-f4. Once again the combination of White's dark-squared Bishop and Knight on 
b5 tie Black up on the Queenside. White has an edge both in position and in 
future plans.} *

