1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4 Bf5 4. f3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. h4 h6 7. e3 c5 {This runs 
into a familiar theme.} 8. h5 {[%csl Rg6] First White gains some space at the 
expense of the g6-Bishop.} Bh7 9. Nb5 {[%cal Gb5c7][%csl Rc7,Gb5,Gf4] This 
really is a powerful option which Black should probably not allow. Whenever 
White gets the Knight to b5 (after Black plays ...c5) it dominates Black's 
Queenside, as ...Na6 is the only sensible reply. Simply put, Black is tied up in 
the knots of the Knight on b5 and the Bishop on f4.} Na6 10. c3 {[%cal 
Gc3b4][%csl Gb4] This pawn move is very useful, preventing any future ...Qa5+ or 
...Nb4 ideas.} Be7 11. Bd3 {[%cal Bd3h7][%csl Rh7] Exchanging off Black's best 
minor piece} Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Nd7 {[%cal Ge7g5,Gd8g5] Black was afraid of the g4-g5 
push.} 13. Ne2 O-O 14. a4 {[%csl Gb5] A strong move, reinforcing the Knight's 
position on b5. It's here to stay for at least a good while yet.} Bf6 {This 
allows White to improve the f4-Bishop's position.} 15. Bd6 {[%csl Gd6,Rf8]} Re8 
16. f4 {[%cal Gf4e5,Bg4g5][%csl Ge5] With a strong grip on the centre, as well 
as ideas of playing g5.} Nb6 17. g5 {This position was covered in model game 
#5.} *

[Event "The Jobava London System"]
