1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4 c6 4. e3 e6 {[%csl Rc8] This solid but passive 
approach is not in any way dangerous to White. It really doesn't fight for the 
initiative.} 5. Bd3 {[%cal Gg1e2,Gg1f3] This Bishop is always well-positioned 
here, while White isn't sure yet whether he wants to put his g1-Knight on e2 (in 
case Black plays ...Bb4) or on f3.} c5 6. Nb5 {[%cal Gb5c7][%csl Rc7] This is 
the normal reply when Black plays ...c5 (without ...a6 of course).} Na6 7. c3 
{[%cal Gc3b4][%csl Gb4] All the standard moves.} c4 8. Bc2 Bd7 9. a4 {[%cal 
Ga4b5][%csl Gb5] Reinforcing the b5-Knight.} Bxb5 10. axb5 Nc7 11. Ba4 {[%cal 
Ga4e8,Bb5b6][%csl Re8] I like White's position. He has the 2 Bishops and at the 
moment the Knight on c7 looks very awkward. A sample line is:} b6 {Otherwise 12. 
b6+ would be an embarassing discovered check.} 12. Nf3 {[%cal Bf3e5,Ge5c6][%csl 
Gc6,Ge5] This Knight will be very strongly positioned on e5.} Bd6 13. Ne5 O-O 
14. Qf3 {[%cal Bf3h3,Ba4c2,Bg2g4,Bg4g5] White can continue in standard 
London-system style with Qh3, Bc2 and g4-g5 with an attack on Black's King.} *

