1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4 c6 4. e3 e6 {This solid but passive approach is not 
in any way dangerous to White. It really doesn't fight for the initiative.} 5. 
Bd3 Bd6 6. Qf3 {[%cal Bg2g4,Bh2h4,Be1c1] This is an unusual move in this line so 
early, but it takes advantage of the fact that Black has played e6 blocking in 
his light-squared Bishop. This move will not only most likely be unexpected - it 
has merit in its own right.} O-O 7. g4 {[%cal Bg4g5][%csl Rf6] As soon as Black 
castles Kingside, White seeks out the initiative on that side of the board.} 
Bxf4 8. Qxf4 {I very much like White's development, space and the start of a 
Kingside initiative.} Nbd7 9. h4 {[%cal Bg4g6,Bh4h6]} Qe7 {[%cal Be6e5] Black 
prepares to push ...e5.} 10. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3e5][%csl Ge5]} Re8 11. g5 {[%csl 
Rf6]} Nh5 12. Qh2 {[%cal Be1c1][%csl Rh5] White has a good position. He is 
prepared to castle Queenside, has a Kingside initiative and the Knight on h5 is 
misplaced.} *

