1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4 c6 4. e3 Bf5 5. f3 {This move contains ideas similar 
to the previous chapter, i.e. g4 and h4 followed by solid development.} e6 {This 
is very cooperative.} 6. g4 {[%cal Bh2h4][%csl Rf5]} Bg6 7. h4 {[%cal 
Bh4h5][%csl Rg6]} h5 8. g5 {[%csl Rf6]} Nfd7 9. Nge2 {[%cal 
Be2f4,Gf4g6,Bf4g3][%csl Rg6] In this exact position, it makes sense not to rush 
into Bd3 because the Bishop on g6 is awkwardly placed and cannot readily be 
supported by a Knight (this is why Kasparov amongst others retreat with Ng8 so 
that the knight can go to e7 supporting the Bishop). It will be awkward for 
Black once our Knight arrives on f4.} *

