[White "Theory 4: 3..."]
[Black "e6 #7 - 4... Bb4"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "09 Theory 4 (3... e6)"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "the-jobava-london-system/course/28333, variation/4877380"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 Bb4 {[%cal Gb4e1][%csl Rc3,Re1]} 5. Bd3 
Bxc3+ {I think this is premature. Black should not break the pin unless he has 
to. It makes sense in the context that White has not yet played Ng1-e2 so White 
has to accept doubled pawns, but the c3 pawn supports d4, covers any ...Nb4 and 
now White will develop the Kingside Knight to the more active square f3 as it is 
not needed on e2.} 6. bxc3 {[%cal Bg1f3,Gc3d4,Ba1b1,Gb1b7][%csl Gc3]} c5 7. dxc5 
{[%cal Bf4d6][%csl Gc5,Gd6] At first glance this may look odd, but it removes 
any chance of Black playing ...c4 and will support Bd6 which will prove 
troublesome for Black.} Qa5 8. Bd6 {[%csl Gc5,Gd6]} Nbd7 9. Ne2 {[%cal Be1g1]} 
Nxc5 10. O-O {[%csl Gd6,Gd3] With roughly equal chances. White currently has the 
bishop pair. If Black wants to remove this feature with Nxd3, White will have 
his structure back and White's dark-squared Bishop is comfortably better than 
Black's light-squared Bishop.} *

