[Event "The Jobava London System"]
[Site "Theory 4 (3... e6)"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 4: 3..."]
[Black "e6 #14 - 4... Bb4"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "09 Theory 4 (3... e6)"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "the-jobava-london-system/course/28333, variation/4893571"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 Bb4 5. Bd3 c5 {Other moves are less worrying 
as they would give White time to play Nge2 with a very comfortable position. 
5... c5 is critical.} 6. dxc5 Nbd7 7. Nge2 Bxc5 {This is not often played but it 
is certainly a viable choice and one we should consider. It looks less natural 
than capturing with the Knight but as we have seen these pieces rapidly get 
kicked back so Bxc5 makes sense.} 8. h3 {[%cal Gf4h2,Gh3g4][%csl Gh2,Gg4] An 
important move, giving White's dark-squared Bishop a square to drop back to if 
Black should play ...Nh5. It also prevents any black piece from moving to g4.} 
a6 {[%cal Ge6e5,Ge5e4][%csl Rd3] Controlling the b5-square. White must be alert 
to e5-e4 trapping his light-squared Bishop.} 9. Bh2 {[%cal Ge6e4,Be1g1][%csl 
Gh2] Ensuring any e5 advance does not come with tempo.} Qe7 10. O-O O-O 11. e4 
{[%cal Be4d5,Be4e5][%csl Ge4] This important move challenges Black's centre and 
intends to free up squares for the white pieces.} dxe4 12. Nxe4 {[%csl Ge4] With 
equal chances. Both sides will seek to centralise. There are few weaknesses to 
exploit.} *

