O-O) play the typical break e4!} c5 {The most logical move in conjunction with 
the earlier ...a6, which made Nb5 impossible for us.} 6. dxc5 {[%cal 
Gc3a4,Ga4b6][%csl Rb6] White's automatic answer to ...c5 when there is a Bishop 
on d3. Otherwise ...c4, gaining a tempo for Black, is very annoying.} Bxc5 7. 
Nf3 {[%cal Be1g1,Be3e4] Simple development. White lacks a bit of space at the 
moment, but once e4 is played all will be ok. We have seen this idea already in 
Theory 4, and it worked out well for White.} Nc6 8. O-O {White is now fully 
developed and must come up with a middlegame plan.} b5 {This is a way for Black 
to advance and gain immediate space on the Queenside. This shouldn't deter us 
from our natural plan though.} 9. e4 {[%csl Ge4,Rd5,Re8] White must play this 
advance in this variation; otherwise it is not clear how to proceed.} b4 {Other 
options are very similar to what we see after 8... O-O.} 10. exd5 {White is 
better after this. Here is a sample line.} exd5 11. Na4 {[%csl Rc5]} Be7 12. Ne5 
{[%cal Ga4c5,Bf4e5,Be5d4][%csl Gc5,Gd4,Rd5] Black has some noticeable 
weaknesses, mainly the isolated pawn on d5 but also the c5-square. White can 
continue by gaining control of d4, most likely by playing Bxe5 and Bd4. After 
that Nc5 and b6 become options, and later in the game Black's pawn on d5 will 
become a real target.} *

[Event "The Jobava London System"]
[Site "Theory 5 (3... a6)"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
