than the Queenside. The idea of g6 is a key thing to remember in this position.} 
Nc6 8. a3 ({The choice of Magnus, and a good one as it prevents a black piece 
from landing on b4, particularly the bishop. ....Bb4 is a move that many Jobava 
London System players would perhaps prefer to avoid.} 8. h4 {, simply getting on 
with things, was the other option.}) b5 9. h4 {Supporting g5 in the short term, 
but as we will see the pawn will not stop at h4. The plan of Kingside 
expansion/pressure should be clear. h5 and g6 is one breakthrough to remember.} 
Bb7 10. h5 {This opens up two main concepts. • 1) g6 at the right moment; • 
2) Bh3 with pressure against e6.} Nb6 {Logically aiming for ...Nc4.} 11. Qd2 
{[%cal Bd4c5,Be1c1,Bf1h3,Bf1d3,Bh1h3]} ({This is better than} 11. Ne5 {, which 
Magnus played against Fabiano. White keeps things flexible and may even capture 
on c5 followed up with Queenside castling, a brave idea! Let's take a look at a 
couple of options that Black may try here.}) Nc4 {Black dives in! This forceful 
move seems to be one of Black's best options.} 12. Bxc4 dxc4 {Opening the Bishop 
on b7.} 13. Rh3 {[%cal Gb7h1,Gh3f3,Bf3e5][%csl Rh1,Rf3]} ({A useful prophylactic 
move. White gets ready with Ne5 in some cases.} 13. dxc5 {runs into} 13... e5 
$1) b4 14. axb4 cxb4 15. Na4 c3 {[%cal Bb2c3,Bb4c3,Bf8b4] Aiming for ...Bb4.} 
16. Qd3 {[%cal Bb2b3][%csl Ga4]} cxb2 {Otherwise b3 from White secures 
everything on the Queenside.} 17. Nxb2 {[%cal Be3e4,Bh5h6,Bg5g6,Bb2c4][%csl Ge5] 
With an interesting position where White's chances are slightly to be preferred. 
This is because White has many more options to break with a pawn - g6, h6 and e4 
being the main three.} *

