putting pressure on d5.} Be6 12. O-O-O {[%csl Rd5] Again increasing the pressure 
on the d-file.} Qe7 13. Nb5 {[%cal Gb5c7,Gb5d6]} ({Here} 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. Nxd5 
$6 Bxd5 15. Qxd5 Rad8 {gives Black some initiative for the pawn. Instead we are 
looking to probe the dark squares.}) b6 14. Nec3 {Now White is putting pressure 
on the d5-pawn, while he also has ideas of Bxf6, Nd6 and (after ...Qxf6) Nc7.} 
bxc5 {This is met as follows.} 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Nxd5 {[%cal Gd1d5,Bb5d6][%csl 
Gd5,Gd6,Gd2,Gd1,Rf6,Re7] White is a clean pawn up with a better position.} *

