1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4 g6 4. e3 Bg7 5. h4 O-O 6. h5 {This is the most 
aggressive and best move after Black played 5... O-O. I think Black is inviting 
trouble. White has to be prepared to sacrifice an exchange, but it's well worth 
it.} Nxh5 {This is the type of position which a computer might be able to hold 
as Black but it requires very accurate defence which is well beyond the powers 
of most people.} 7. Rxh5 gxh5 8. Qxh5 {White's plan is not subtle but it doesn't 
need to be. It's a direct attack on Black's King. Currently Black only has his 
dark-squared Bishop defending the King. If he has any realistic chance of 
surviving he will need to bring in reinforcements and blunt White's threats.} 
Nd7 {[%cal Bd7f6] Bringing the Knight quickly to f6 makes a lot of sense to me 
but I can't find any games in my database where it has been played. 
Understandably not many black players accept the sacrifice and those that have 
done so have a very poor record.} 9. Qh2 {[%cal Gh2c7,Bf1d3,Bg1f3,Be1c1][%csl 
Gh2,Rc7,Gf4] Consistent again.} c6 10. Bd3 {[%cal Gd3h7,Gh2h7][%csl Rh7] Already 
threatening mate.} Nf6 {This feels like Black's best shot at holding this 
position, but White still has a wealth of good moves such as Nf3, O-O-O and 
Rh1.} 11. Nf3 {One nice idea to point out here is the following line.} Bg4 12. 
Ne5 {[%cal Ge5g4][%csl Rg4]} Bh5 {Black is attempting to block White's attack 
with ...Bg6, but White can play as follows:} 13. Bxh7+ Kxh7 (13... Nxh7 {allows} 
14. Qxh5 {.}) 14. g4 {[%cal Gh2h7,Be1c1,Ba1h1][%csl Rh5,Rh7] This ensures that 
the lines of attack remain very much open. I think White is objectively better 
and in a practical game Black's position is very difficult to defend.} *

