{In this game we look at what happens when Black aims to counterplay on the 
Queenside with ...c6. I feel this plan is too slow.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 ({We 
prefer the move order} 2. Nc3 g6 3. Bf4 {.}) g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Qd2 h5 {A 
strange but interesting move, taken from lines of the Dragon variation of the 
Sicilian. Black wants to stop White from playing Bh6 at all costs. The downside 
is that White now has an outpost on g5, as he doesn't have to fear ...h6, and 
ideas of playing g2-g4 opening up the Kingside.} 6. O-O-O c6 7. Nf3 {Simple play 
in the centre.} b5 {This all seems rather slow and White now aims to punish 
that.} 8. e5 {White is much better positioned to hit in the centre. This opens 
things up to White's advantage.} dxe5 (8... b4 $1 {was a much better and a more 
typical idea. If the c3-Knight moves Black has ...Nd5, and after} 9. exf6 bxc3 
10. Qxc3 Bxf6 11. Bc4 Nd7 {Black can claim a certain amount of counterplay, but 
I think White is still better.}) 9. Nxe5 ({There was nothing wrong with} 9. dxe5 
Qxd2+ 10. Rxd2 Nfd7 11. e6 $1 {, when Black would be really struggling. For 
example,} 11... fxe6 12. Bd3 Nf8 13. Nxb5 $1 {Tactics!} 13... cxb5 14. Be4 {and 
White is winning.}) Be6 10. Kb1 Qa5 11. a3 ({A rather blunderfull rapid game! 
There was a nice tactic here:} 11. d5 $1 {would have won on the spot! The idea 
is} 11... cxd5 12. Nxd5 Qxd2 13. Nc7+ Kd8 14. Nxe6+ fxe6 15. Rxd2+ {with a 
winning game.}) b4 12. axb4 Qxb4 13. Nb5 {White gets the tactic right the second 
time around. This gains a winning position.} Qxd2 14. Nc7+ Kd8 15. Nxe6+ fxe6 
16. Bxd2 {Black's pawn structure can be described as 'Brexited' - a total bloody 
disaster. White went on to win.} Rg8 17. Ba5+ Kc8 18. Nxg6 Bf8 19. Nf4 Ne4 20. 
Be1 Nd7 21. Nxe6 Kb7 22. f3 Nd6 23. Nc5+ Kc7 24. Bg3 Nb6 25. Ba6 Bg7 26. Rhe1 
Bf6 27. Re6 Raf8 28. Rde1 Rf7 29. Ne4 Bxd4 30. Rd1 Bh8 31. c4 Kd7 32. Rh6 1-0

