Black has to find the more accurate defensive moves. White's plan is to capture 
on c5 in nearly all positions.} Nc6 {This is an interesting choice, as the 
natural 5 d5 leads to nothing after 5... a6. For that reason I would suggest 
that White plays as follows:} 5. Nge2 {Developing and holding the centre 
together.} a6 {Keeping it simple. Other options were worse.} 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. 
Be3 {[%cal Gc3e4,Bf2f3,Bf3e4,Be1g1][%csl Rc6,Rc5,Ra6,Re4] White has good 
compensation for the pawn. Black has numerous pawn weaknesses and is not as well 
developed as White. White should naturally castle and then either aim to win the 
pawn on e4 back, or try the more adventurous f3 idea with Rxf3 to follow. It 
would be nice to see some practical examples of this!} *

