1. d4 e6 2. Nc3 {Bf4 is always worth considering against the early ...e6 
systems. This avoids any issues with ...Bb4.} Nf6 3. e4 {Transposing into a 
French Defence. Of course our main move is Bf4, but I wanted to suggest some 
interesting French Defence side lines. Chess is a mind game and in this case if 
Black is not ready for a French Defence, it would benefit you to have that as an 
option. I am not going to show too much theory, but as an expert in the French I 
thought I would suggest two side lines that are very annoying for Black and 
require a minimum amount of work to learn.} Bb4 {This is simply a mistake.} 4. 
e5 {Black is getting pushed around.} Ne4 (4... Nd5 5. Qg4 {is a better way to 
play for Black, but White is doing well as he can always play Bd2, stopping any 
threats on the e1-a5 diagonal.}) 5. Qg4 {[%cal Gg4e4,Gg4g7][%csl Rg7,Re4] With a 
winning advantage!} Nxc3 6. Qxg7 {[%cal Bc2c3][%csl Rh8,Rc3,Rb4] Black has no 
good checks with his Knight. Everything is met with c3.} Rf8 7. a3 {[%cal 
Ba3b4,Bc1h6,Gh6f8][%csl Rc3,Rb4,Rf8] White will win his piece back and retain 
the threat of Bh6.} *

[Event "The Jobava London System"]
[Site "Theory 11-13 (3... Bb4, 2... Bb4 and 1... c5)"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. e4!? - French tranpositions"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "22 Theory 11-13 (3... Bb4, 2... Bb4 and 1... c5)"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "the-jobava-london-system/course/28333, variation/5110126"]

1. d4 e6 2. Nc3 {Bf4 is always worth considering against the early ...e6 
systems. This avoids any issues with ...Bb4.} Nf6 3. e4 {Transposing into a 
French Defence. Of course our main move is Bf4, but I wanted to suggest some 
interesting French Defence side lines. Chess is a mind game and in this case if 
Black is not ready for a French Defence, it would benefit you to have that as an 
option. I am not going to show too much theory, but as an expert in the French I 
thought I would suggest two side lines that are very annoying for Black and 
require a minimum amount of work to learn.} d5 {Black should certainly play a 
French. Otherwise he is just worse.} ({After} 3... c5 {the move} 4. dxc5 {leads 
into the positions that we research in the 1... c5 theory section.} ({I would 
also be tempted to play} 4. d5 {here, which is just a bit better for White.})) 
4. e5 {[%csl Rf6] The simplest move to play. Of course, there are other options 
that you may want to explore yourself.} Nfd7 5. Nce2 {[%cal Bc2c3,Bf2f4][%csl 
Gd4,Ge5] This is a rare sideline, but a move that has been favoured by Anand 
among others. White wants to keep a strong centre by meeting the move ...c5 with 
c3. This line lets you avoid having to learn lots of theory, yet at the same 
time it is easy to play and positionally sound.} c5 6. c3 {The idea behind Nce2. 
If Black now plays passively, White will always have an advantage due to his 
strong centre.} Nc6 7. f4 {[%cal Bg1f3][%csl Gc3,Gd4,Ge5,Gf4] Yes please! This 
is a pretty awesome pawn formation. I know from playing on the Black side of 
this that things can become very tricky. If Black doesn't break somehow (which 
is tough!) then White has a great game due to the space advantage.} Qb6 {[%csl 
Rd4] Hitting d4 in typical fashion. This is best. If Black doesn't play actively 
then White will do the following things: • 1) Aim to play a3 and b4, Gaining 
more space on the Queenside; • 2) Play h4!, gaining space and stopping any 
idea of ...g5 that Black might be thinking on the Kingside; • 3) Finish 
development with Nf3, Ng3, Bd3 and O-O; • 4) Start an attack with the space 
advantage. f4-f5 is normally one option.} 8. Nf3 Be7 9. a3 {[%cal Bb2b4] White 
might as well aim to take more space with b4!} O-O 10. h4 {[%cal Bf3g5][%csl 
Rh7] Anand's idea. Ng5 is now sometimes a possibility.} f6 {Black must break up 
the centre with this move. Otherwise Black will just be suffocated.} 11. Rh3 
{[%cal Gh3c3,Bh3g3,Gg3g7] A weird but useful move! The Rook helps defend the 
centre and sometimes it can also pop to g3, applying pressure to Black's 
Kingside.} Na5 {Shirov aims to find some squares on the Queenside for his 
Knight.} 12. b4 {[%csl Ra5,Rc5] Gaining more space. And why not!} cxb4 13. axb4 
Nc4 14. h5 (14. Ng3 {was played by Anand against Shirov, but this gave Shirov 
the option of sacrificing with} 14... fxe5 15. fxe5 Ncxe5 16. dxe5 Nxe5 {, which 
is not what we want.}) {14. h5 gains more space, and now Black's sacrifice 
doesn't work as well. Let's see why.} fxe5 15. fxe5 Ndxe5 {Something to watch 
out for, but here it just doesn't work.} 16. dxe5 Nxe5 17. Nxe5 Qf2+ 18. Kd2 
{[%cal Bd2c2,Bh3f3] White is much better. Black just doesn't have enough play 
for all the material that he has sacrificed.} *

