1. d4 e6 2. Nc3 Bb4 {This move should not be of major concern to White, as it 
often transposes to positions we have already seen. However, this line should be 
taken note of, because there can be some differences on the road to these more 
familiar positions.} 3. Bf4 c5 {[%csl Rd4] This is a good example of where 2... 
Bb4 has independent significance. This position can only arise when the Bishop 
moves to b4 on move 2.} 4. e3 {[%cal Ge3d4]} d5 5. Nge2 {[%cal Ge2c3,Ba2a3] 
White is preparing a3 when he can recapture on c3 with his Knight.} cxd4 6. exd4 
Nf6 7. a3 Be7 8. Nb5 {[%cal Gb5c7,Gf4c7,Be2c3,Bf1d3][%csl Rc7] This is our 
standard manoeuvre if Black has forgotten to play ...a6. White can follow up 
with Nec3, Bd3 and castling.} *

