1. d4 e6 2. Nc3 Bb4 {This move should not be of major concern to White, as it 
often transposes to positions we have already seen. However, this line should be 
taken note of, because there can be some differences on the road to these more 
familiar positions.} 3. Bf4 c5 {This is a good example of where 2... Bb4 has 
independent significance. This position can only arise when the Bishop moves to 
b4 on move 2.} 4. e3 d5 5. Nge2 cxd4 6. exd4 Nf6 7. a3 Bd6 {[%cal Gd6f4] This is 
the most active square to retreat to and prevents Nb5.} 8. Qd2 {[%cal Be1c1] We 
can keep the tension on f4 a little longer and first castle long.} O-O 9. O-O-O 
{[%cal Bc1b1][%csl Rc8] There are chances for both sides here. The opposite side 
castling should lead to attacks on different sides of the board. White should 
focus on direct moves when possible. Here is a sample line:} Nc6 10. Kb1 a6 11. 
g4 {Very aggressive.} Nxg4 12. Rg1 {[%cal Gg1g7][%csl Rg7]} Nxf2 {Instead, Black 
should probably exchange on f4 and then return with ...Nf6.} 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. 
Qh6 {[%cal Gg1g8,Bh6g7][%csl Rg7]} g6 15. Nf4 {[%cal Bf4h5] White's threat of 
Nh5 is too strong.} *

