1. d4 e6 2. Nc3 Bb4 {This move should not be of major concern to White, as it 
often transposes to positions we have already seen. However, this line should be 
taken note of, because there can be some differences on the road to these more 
familiar positions.} 3. Bf4 c5 {This is a good example of where 2... Bb4 has 
independent significance. This position can only arise when the Bishop moves to 
b4 on move 2.} 4. e3 Qa5 {This attempt to undermine c3 is somewhat artificial. 
White can gain a good position with careful play.} 5. Nge2 cxd4 6. exd4 Nf6 7. 
a3 {White has got this move in time which means that the best option for Black's 
bishops is to retreat. This suggests Black's early sorties have not been 
justified.} Be7 8. Qd3 O-O 9. O-O-O {With a similar type of position we have 
seen. White should have no fear of a sacrificial attack on the Queenside. 
Reinforcements are some way away and the following is a quick example of White 
using his lead in development to strike in the centre.} Nc6 10. d5 {[%cal 
Gd1d7][%csl Rd7] If Black does not play ...d5 himself, we can advance like this 
and generate some pressure on the d5-file.} exd5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. Qxd5 Qxd5 13. 
Rxd5 {[%cal Be2c3,Bf1e2,Bh1d1][%csl Rd7] The half open d-file and isolated 
d-pawn give White a very comfortable position.} *

[Event "The Jobava London System"]
[Site "Theory 11-13 (3... Bb4, 2... Bb4 and 1... c5)"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 13: 1... c5 - Overview"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "22 Theory 11-13 (3... Bb4, 2... Bb4 and 1... c5)"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "the-jobava-london-system/course/28333, variation/4883134"]

1. d4 c5 {My experience has taught me that when Black plays ...c5 on move 1 or 
2, he is hoping that White will respond witrh the natural looking push d5 which 
steers the game towards Benoni-type positions. This is perfectly reasonable, but 
why should we play into our opponent's hands when we have a perfectly decent 
alternative which avoids our opponent's wishes?} 2. dxc5 {This has been the 
choice of Mamedyarov on more than one occasion.} e6 (2... Qa5+ 3. Nc3 Qxc5 4. e4 
Nf6 5. Be3 Qa5 6. Qd2 $14 {White has a lead in development and greater central 
control. Developing with moves such as Rd1, Nf3, Be2 and O-O should lead to a 
comfortable game.}) (2... Nf6 3. Nc3 e6 4. e4 {I like this move best 
particularly because Black's natural reply is not good.} 4... Bxc5 5. e5 Qb6 $6 
{This is the line White must know, as figuring out the best moves over the board 
may not be that easy. Other moves like 5... Ng8 simply give White more space and 
much greater central control.} 6. exf6 $1 {A move which leads to a large 
advantage for White.} 6... Bxf2+ 7. Ke2 Bxg1 {This actually 'threatens' 
perpetual check with Qf2 and Qd4 and this is why White must be prepared. You 
need to know the following line.} 8. Rxg1 $1 Qxg1 9. Qd6 Nc6 10. Be3 Qh1 11. 
fxg7 Rg8 12. Ne4 $18) 3. Nc3 Nf6 (3... Bxc5 4. Ne4 Be7 5. Nd6+ Bxd6 6. Qxd6 $14 
{I think it's fair to say that White already has a slight edge, given that Black 
has lost his best minor piece for a Knight and has dark square weaknesses. There 
is nothing immediate but developing normally will assuredly lead to a 
comfortable game.}) 4. e4 {This transposes to the line looked at previously. 
Let's briefly consider if Black is aware that 4... Bxc5 is not good.} Qa5 (4... 
Nc6 5. Be3 b6 6. cxb6 axb6 7. a3 $14 {This simple move suggests that Black will 
not get anywhere near enough compensation for the gambitted pawn.}) 5. Bd3 Bxc5 
6. Nf3 d6 7. a3 a6 8. Bg5 {White threatens b4, so Black has no time for a move 
like 8... Nbd7.} Qd8 9. O-O {White has a clear lead in development, more space 
and better central control. It feels safe to say that Black is a long way from 
anything like what he wanted when he played 1... c5.} *

