1. d4 c5 {My experience has taught me that when Black plays ...c5 on move 1 or 
2, he is hoping that White will respond with the natural looking push d5. This 
steers the game towards Benoni-type positions. 2. d5 is perfectly reasonable, 
but why should we play into our opponent's hands when we have a perfectly decent 
alternative which avoids our opponent's wishes?} 2. dxc5 {[%cal Bb1c3,Be2e4] 
This has been the choice of Mamedyarov on more than one occasion.} Qa5+ 3. Nc3 
Qxc5 4. e4 {[%cal Bc1e3,Bd1d2] We stake our fair share of the centre and prepare 
to develop with Be3 and Qd2.} Nf6 5. Be3 {[%csl Rc5]} Qa5 6. Qd2 {[%cal 
Bg1f3,Bf1e2,Ba1d1,Be1g1] White has a lead in development and greater central 
control. Developing with moves such as Rd1, Nf3, Be2 and O-O should lead to a 
comfortable game.} *

