1. d4 f5 {Of course this is a good move ;-)} 2. Nc3 {It makes sense to stick to 
our main move. I could have suggested a number of options here, but 2. Nc3 fits 
our system the best.} e6 {This position can also be reached via 1... e6 2. Nc3 
f5?! This has been known to be a mistake by Black for a long time. Black should 
fight against White's advance e4 and not encourage it. White is simply better 
after the following moves.} 3. e4 {[%csl Ge4,Gd4] White is already better! Black 
should really avoid this position. White has easy development and chances to 
attack Black's King on the light squares.} fxe4 {Other options are even worse 
for Black.} 4. Nxe4 Be7 (4... Nf6 5. Bd3 {is similar.}) 5. Nf3 {[%cal 
Bf1d3,Bd1e2][%csl Ge4,Gf3] White's pieces flow into the game.} Nf6 {Black must 
develop.} 6. Bd3 {[%cal Bd1e2,Bc1d2,Be1c1,Bh2h4,Gf3g5,Ge4g5][%csl Gg5] White has 
a number of ideas. I would be aiming to punish Black with such simple moves as 
Qe2, Bd2, O-O-O, h4 and put one of the Knights on g5! White always has ideas of 
starting an attack against h7. Kasparov vs. Fernandez, 1991, continued as 
follows:} d6 7. Qe2 O-O 8. h4 {White is ready to support a Knight landing on g5. 
This is already horrible for Black.} Qe8 9. Nfg5 {[%cal Gd3h7,Gg5h7][%csl Rh7] 
Targeting h7.} Nxe4 10. Qxe4 {[%csl Rh7]} Rf5 11. g4 {[%cal Gd3h7,Gg4f5][%csl 
Rf5] and Black could have resigned.} *

