1. d4 f5 {Of course this is a good move ;)} 2. Nc3 {It makes sense to stick to 
our main move. I could have suggested a number of options here, but 2. Nc3 fits 
our system the best.} Nf6 3. Bg5 {In this case I believe the Bishop is better 
placed on g5. This is because one of White's main ideas is to capture on f6 and 
play e4. You can experiment with Bf4 as in the normal Jobava London System, but 
Bg5 is more testing for Black.} g6 {This is what a dedicated Leningrad player or 
fool would play! There are a couple of options here, but one is clearly best.} 
4. h4 {[%cal Bh4h5][%csl Rg6,Rh7,Re8] This is a very dangerous move for Black to 
deal with, as the natural move allows White the initiative.} Bg7 5. h5 {[%csl 
Rg6] With a big attack.} Nxh5 {This is asking for it! Saying that, it was 
already looking difficult as White was aiming to play h6, forcing Black to 
undevelop his Bishop.} 6. e4 {[%cal Bh1h5][%csl Rh5,Re8]} ({Rxh5 is coming! In 
actual fact,} 6. Rxh5 {was also strong on this move.}) Nf6 7. exf5 gxf5 8. Bxf6 
Bxf6 9. Qh5+ {[%csl Re8,Rf5]} Kf8 10. Qxf5 {[%cal Bg1f3,Bf1d3,Be1c1][%csl 
Rf8,Rh7] When Black's King is just too weak. White can play normal moves and 
gain a great position.} *

